Files writing without using stream writer. 

When you're generating large synthetic datasets or building automation utilities, you don’t always need the full control of StreamWriter. For bulk, sequential writes, File.WriteAllLines is a surprisingly efficient abstraction — and under the hood, it still uses buffered I/O.

🔍 Why File.WriteAllLines Works Well for Bulk Output
File.WriteAllLines internally:
Allocates a UTF‑8 encoded stream
Buffers writes efficiently
Flushes once at the end
Avoids manual disposal logic
Reduces boilerplate and cognitive overhead
For workloads where the entire dataset fits comfortably in memory, this is both fast and clean.

🧪 VB.NET Implementation
=========================
Dim numberlist As IEnumerable(Of String) =
    Enumerable.Range(1, 400000).Select(Function(i) i.ToString("000000"))

File.WriteAllLines("D:\output_vb.txt",
                   numberlist.ToArray(),
                   Encoding.UTF8)

🧪 C# Implementation
=================
IEnumerable<string> numberslist =
    Enumerable.Range(1, 400000).Select(x => x.ToString("000000"));

File.WriteAllLines("D:\\output_csharp.txt",
                   numberslist.ToArray(),
                   Encoding.UTF8);

📈 Performance Notes
Enumerable.Range is extremely efficient — it avoids allocations and iterates lazily.
Converting to an array (ToArray()) ensures a single pass and a contiguous memory block.
UTF‑8 encoding keeps file size compact and predictable.
For 400k lines, memory footprint is modest (~3–4 MB depending on padding).
Disk write time is dominated by I/O throughput, not CPU.
If you need streaming for very large datasets (millions of lines), StreamWriter or FileStream with chunked writes becomes the better choice. But for mid‑sized synthetic data generation, this approach is ideal.

🧰 When to Use This Pattern
Use File.WriteAllLines when:
The dataset fits in memory
You want clean, readable code
You’re generating test data, mock files, or ETL inputs
You want predictable UTF‑8 output without manual stream handling
